WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.920
My name is Tom Mock, I'm a product manager here at Posit,

00:00:02.920 --> 00:00:05.860
and I oversee the Positron IDE,

00:00:05.860 --> 00:00:08.760
as well as our studio and Posit Workbench,

00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:12.440
as well as AI integrations into those tools,

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:15.840
both in kind of some of the add-in space for our studio,

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:16.879
and we'll be talking about today

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:19.340
with Positron via Positron Assistant.

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:22.240
I think with a lot of the tools

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:24.080
that we've talked about today,

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:25.879
there's kind of the integration points,

00:00:25.879 --> 00:00:29.240
as well as the applications you might build out of that.

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:30.559
With Positron Assistant,

00:00:30.559 --> 00:00:32.880
and what I'm talking about in my section,

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:35.959
it'll mostly be focused on the developer tooling.

00:00:35.959 --> 00:00:39.080
So what is the experience that you as a data scientist,

00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:42.580
data analyst, applied scientist are doing inside your IDE?

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:46.240
Positron Assistant looks something like this

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:47.560
inside of Positron.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:49.200
If you're not aware of what Positron is,

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:51.799
it's a brand new IDE that we've released

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:53.680
into general availability on desktop,

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:56.759
and that's coming out in Posit Workbench here shortly.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:00:59.759
But Positron Assistant is a subtool

00:00:59.759 --> 00:01:02.560
within the Positron IDE that provides

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:04.360
kind of a unified chat interface

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:06.839
with different backend model providers.

00:01:07.919 --> 00:01:10.519
It's a GNI client, native to Positron,

00:01:10.519 --> 00:01:14.199
a client meaning that Posit doesn't actually see

00:01:14.199 --> 00:01:15.739
any of the data that you're sending.

00:01:15.739 --> 00:01:18.800
It's purely between you and the model provider you choose.

00:01:19.959 --> 00:01:22.639
And to that point, it's built off this idea

00:01:22.639 --> 00:01:25.680
of a future with your bring your own model provider backend.

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:27.040
So I'll talk about a little bit more,

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:29.459
but right now it's very anthropic centric

00:01:29.459 --> 00:01:33.760
because of how good their cloud models are at code generation

00:01:34.599 --> 00:01:36.599
but we layer on our own system prompt

00:01:36.599 --> 00:01:38.480
and other contexts on top of that.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:41.160
And ultimately we expect that different customers,

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:44.279
especially like yourselves or different user groups

00:01:44.279 --> 00:01:46.720
would actually be bringing some of your own

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.440
potential self-hosted models

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:51.000
or routing to many different model providers.

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:54.199
Part of the play here,

00:01:54.199 --> 00:01:56.400
part of the kind of reason why we're investing

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:58.519
so heavily into this space

00:01:58.519 --> 00:02:01.320
is there's lots of great extensions out there.

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:05.239
You can use Google Gemini or AWS Q or Klein

00:02:05.239 --> 00:02:07.199
or all these other, Claude code,

00:02:07.199 --> 00:02:10.520
all these tools inside of tools like Positron.

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:12.479
But a lot of them, if not all of them

00:02:12.479 --> 00:02:15.919
are missing the context of what you do in memory

00:02:15.919 --> 00:02:20.160
or in the ephemeral state beyond just the files on disk.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:23.080
And I'll talk a little bit about what that means.

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:24.759
Again, if you wanted to try this out

00:02:24.759 --> 00:02:27.240
you could download Positron desktop today

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.399
and try it out in your desktop environment.

00:02:29.399 --> 00:02:32.199
Or if you are using Posit Workbench

00:02:32.199 --> 00:02:34.960
it'll be available there shortly in our upcoming release

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:37.240
that is due out in days to weeks.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:42.279
As I mentioned, part of the story here

00:02:42.279 --> 00:02:46.679
is that the AI space is moving really rapidly.

00:02:46.679 --> 00:02:48.679
And so there's lots of different models out there,

00:02:48.679 --> 00:02:50.119
different model providers.

00:02:50.119 --> 00:02:52.479
And again, Positron Assistant is trying to be

00:02:53.279 --> 00:02:56.080
a general unified interface to them.

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:58.720
So today that means we support two providers.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:03.119
We support Anthropic directly via API key for chat.

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:06.479
And then we have GitHub Copilot for inline completions.

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:10.119
We're also exploring GitHub Copilot for chat modalities

00:03:10.119 --> 00:03:12.160
along with a host of other providers,

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:16.960
your Databricks, Snowflake, your AWS Bedrock and the like

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:21.000
that provide models both from Anthropic and others.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.960
Lastly, and again, I wanna emphasize this

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:25.679
in terms of for this group of people

00:03:25.679 --> 00:03:27.919
in terms of some of the data privacy

00:03:27.919 --> 00:03:30.039
or potentially cost efficiency,

00:03:30.039 --> 00:03:32.000
I've talked to a lot of different people

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.919
that also are self-hosting their own models

00:03:34.919 --> 00:03:37.839
whether that's for, again, privacy reasons

00:03:37.839 --> 00:03:40.679
or very specific datasets are not allowed

00:03:40.679 --> 00:03:42.639
to go out to these cloud providers

00:03:42.639 --> 00:03:45.080
even with the contracts you have in place.

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:48.039
So we also wanna support OpenAI compatible endpoints

00:03:48.039 --> 00:03:50.160
in the future to allow you to basically

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:51.479
bring your own model.

00:03:51.479 --> 00:03:54.199
And that's intended to be used with high quality models

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:56.880
but like with models that you are serving up

00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:58.479
or providing access to.

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:03.199
While I've talked a little bit prior

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:05.720
about it being like the sidebar chat modality,

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:07.559
it also offers inline chat.

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:09.919
So again, even without code completion

00:04:09.919 --> 00:04:11.360
because some of these model providers

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:14.320
don't offer an inline completion model,

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:17.720
there's still support for things like inline chat.

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:18.920
And importantly, whether you're working

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:20.760
on the sidebar chat or the inline chat,

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:23.239
you still have access to all of the custom contexts

00:04:23.239 --> 00:04:25.160
I'll talk about in a second.

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:27.679
And you might have an example of like I have a source file,

00:04:27.679 --> 00:04:30.440
I can open it up and I can say, ask a question

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:32.799
and it will actually inject a little portion

00:04:32.799 --> 00:04:35.440
that then opens up a temporary chat

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:37.399
just within that line of code.

00:04:37.399 --> 00:04:39.760
And it grabs that line of code you're working on

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:42.119
and a little bit of extra context around it

00:04:42.119 --> 00:04:45.040
as well as all the in-memory context

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:48.359
that things like your console in R or Python

00:04:48.359 --> 00:04:50.040
or your in-memory data frames

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:52.519
or other objects you've defined.

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:55.119
So again, I'm gonna talk a lot about sidebar chat

00:04:55.119 --> 00:04:56.359
and that's what you'll see,

00:04:56.359 --> 00:04:58.119
but just know that inline chat

00:04:58.119 --> 00:05:01.519
is also kind of a critical capability that overlaps.

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:05.200
So again, at the very beginning

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:06.799
kind of coming back around to this,

00:05:06.799 --> 00:05:08.679
I said, part of why we're doing this

00:05:08.679 --> 00:05:11.000
is we want to enrich the context

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.279
beyond the files on disk, right?

00:05:13.279 --> 00:05:15.920
All the AI tooling out there within an IDE

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.839
largely says, hey, you're working in a source file,

00:05:18.839 --> 00:05:21.359
we take that source file, package it up,

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:25.559
send it to the model as a prompt along with your ask

00:05:25.559 --> 00:05:27.959
and then you get a response back.

00:05:27.959 --> 00:05:29.600
Positron goes a step further

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:33.000
and uses a technology called tool calling internally

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.040
to provide additional tools that the model is aware of.

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:38.720
These tools could be things like,

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:40.720
hey, if the user asks about something

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:43.239
like the current session, right?

00:05:43.239 --> 00:05:45.239
The model can ask Positron,

00:05:45.239 --> 00:05:47.359
what is the user working in, right?

00:05:47.359 --> 00:05:49.040
They're working in an R environment

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:51.519
and we can report back information like,

00:05:51.519 --> 00:05:55.880
oh, your R console is R version 4.4.3

00:05:55.880 --> 00:05:57.760
and inside of your session, right?

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:00.640
Not just the actual console, but inside of your session,

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:04.279
you've defined a data frame like this Olympics dataset

00:06:04.279 --> 00:06:06.160
and here's the schema, how big it is,

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:08.880
the column names, the number of rows,

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:11.279
other information that's loaded there in memory.

00:06:12.239 --> 00:06:15.480
And we can repeat this for many other kind of tools

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:16.799
that are available inside of Positron,

00:06:16.799 --> 00:06:20.480
like the plot pane, session input and output,

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:22.279
you know, the console history

00:06:22.279 --> 00:06:24.959
and other tools that we wanna make available over time

00:06:24.959 --> 00:06:26.559
within the IDE.

00:06:26.559 --> 00:06:29.480
But importantly, this type of novel context

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:32.160
is going beyond what a lot of the other AI tooling

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:36.679
are providing in addition to all of the like source files

00:06:36.679 --> 00:06:39.839
and the training data and other things that are available

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:41.880
outside of the memory context.

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:47.239
Importantly, this also works for Python,

00:06:47.239 --> 00:06:50.799
you know, Positron is intended to be a polyglot IDE,

00:06:50.799 --> 00:06:53.399
so the things you can do in R, you can also do in Python,

00:06:53.399 --> 00:06:55.880
the things you can do in Python, you can also do in R.

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:57.359
So you could ask a similar question

00:06:57.359 --> 00:07:00.000
and it can report back about a Python console

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.559
as well as the in-memory state on that.

00:07:05.359 --> 00:07:07.480
Now, to dive in a little bit further,

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:11.119
now that we've kind of defined this idea of tool calling,

00:07:11.119 --> 00:07:14.079
you could imagine I might be building applications

00:07:14.079 --> 00:07:16.000
or might be doing an analysis

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.040
and I'm working with specific datasets

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:19.559
that have been defined, right?

00:07:19.559 --> 00:07:22.359
So when I'm asking questions,

00:07:22.359 --> 00:07:24.959
it actually can ask about, you know,

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:27.359
what is this data frame I have defined?

00:07:28.279 --> 00:07:31.160
This new data frame contains these columns

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:34.279
and it kind of describes them or has information about them,

00:07:34.279 --> 00:07:37.799
the encoding, the schema of that data.

00:07:37.799 --> 00:07:40.720
So again, rather than you having to manually encode this

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:43.959
into your source file or to manually, you know,

00:07:43.959 --> 00:07:45.480
write it out in your literal prompt,

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:49.640
like for column one, which is MPG do X,

00:07:49.640 --> 00:07:51.600
you could actually just have the model

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:54.040
passively know this information

00:07:54.040 --> 00:07:55.760
as you're asking other questions,

00:07:55.760 --> 00:07:59.040
where that better context should lead to better results

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:01.399
or better kind of outputs from your model.

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:05.799
This of course, isn't limited to just data frames.

00:08:05.799 --> 00:08:08.480
It could be other objects you've defined in memory

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:10.720
and again, works across languages.

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:14.880
The other example that I think is really neat

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:18.000
is because you have an active console, right?

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.079
There's context there.

00:08:20.079 --> 00:08:22.160
And one of the ways I like to highlight this

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:25.799
is kind of nuanced is you can imagine all IDEs, right?

00:08:25.799 --> 00:08:28.559
Can say you have a static analysis error

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:30.000
in your source file,

00:08:30.040 --> 00:08:32.880
meaning you've done something like misspelled

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:34.799
a function name.

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:37.200
And even without LLMs, right?

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.440
Your IDE can say, hey, there's a problem here.

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:41.440
You should probably fix it.

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:44.760
However, if a data frame or a data object

00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:48.640
is missing a column, your script doesn't know that.

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:51.320
And the language server protocol or the layer on top,

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:53.760
the static analysis doesn't know that.

00:08:53.760 --> 00:08:55.440
But when you run that code,

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:59.400
basically these runtime errors versus kind of linting errors,

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:01.919
that's where positron assist can also help out.

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:03.760
Where as you're building up an analysis

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:05.640
or debugging something,

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:09.320
it has context to not only what is the source file showing,

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:11.039
but what are the error messages,

00:09:11.039 --> 00:09:13.440
the literal trace back that's in the console.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:14.919
It can pull that in and say,

00:09:14.919 --> 00:09:18.640
oh, I see the source file in the lines you're working on.

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:19.479
I see the error.

00:09:19.479 --> 00:09:23.000
Let me help you fix that within all of that context.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:24.960
And again, both R and Python,

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:27.919
not just limited to one language.

00:09:27.919 --> 00:09:31.039
So I like to use that for examples of, again,

00:09:31.039 --> 00:09:32.880
the in-memory state is important

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:36.719
and the runtime details are very, very important.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:41.080
You can also go one step further.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:43.719
And for a lot of models out there,

00:09:43.719 --> 00:09:46.640
they can interpret graphics or images.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:50.080
So we make use of this for viewing things like plots,

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:53.679
where not only can the model and positron assistant say,

00:09:53.679 --> 00:09:56.719
oh, we have source code to generate a plot

00:09:56.719 --> 00:09:58.760
and we can interpret and work on that,

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:01.320
the actual source code of how you got there,

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:03.440
but the actual plot that you generated

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:05.719
can be included as context.

00:10:05.719 --> 00:10:07.840
So it could help with things like,

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:09.960
oh, well, this looks overly compact.

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:11.840
Do you want to change the dimensions?

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:14.960
Where your source code may not have anything to do

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:18.880
with the XY coordinates or the size of the chart,

00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:22.479
but we can see in the plot pane that the graphic is too small

00:10:22.479 --> 00:10:25.640
or what are the other ways of showing a distribution

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:27.919
or this data in a different way,

00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:29.840
or help me generate alternative text

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:33.440
or a description of this plot and many other situations.

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:39.000
And then lastly, around the session state,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:39.919
there's all that information

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:41.919
about what language is active in the console,

00:10:41.919 --> 00:10:43.840
R or Python, what version,

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:45.840
what packages are available

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:47.200
in terms of they've been loaded

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:48.880
or available in the environment.

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:50.960
What was the last execution or the error?

00:10:50.960 --> 00:10:53.080
Help me fix those things.

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:55.000
So all of these little pieces of context

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:56.479
when you add them together,

00:10:56.479 --> 00:10:59.200
give you a lot more context to provide to the model

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:00.640
to generate better results

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:02.599
based upon what you're actually working on.

00:11:02.599 --> 00:11:04.799
Rather than having to manually specify,

00:11:04.799 --> 00:11:07.599
here are the 10 packages that I want to use,

00:11:07.599 --> 00:11:09.799
it has some of that context passively.

00:11:11.239 --> 00:11:14.200
Importantly, while you could imagine some of this data,

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:16.159
you're like, wow, that's a lot of data,

00:11:16.159 --> 00:11:20.000
but I'm pretty sensitive about what data is going across.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:21.039
Again, importantly,

00:11:21.039 --> 00:11:23.599
this is between you and the model provider.

00:11:23.599 --> 00:11:26.760
So you've already vetted a model provider

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:28.320
to allow you to ask questions

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:29.799
or you have some type of contract

00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:31.719
or negotiation with them.

00:11:31.719 --> 00:11:34.119
So importantly, like we as a company as Posit,

00:11:34.119 --> 00:11:36.359
we're not trying to inject ourselves in the middle

00:11:36.359 --> 00:11:39.400
or really think about like hosting models,

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:40.760
we're providing a client.

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:43.479
So that relationship is between you

00:11:43.479 --> 00:11:45.520
and the model provider

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:48.520
and the data that's being transferred back and forth.

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:51.559
So it's only being sent to the large language model API,

00:11:51.559 --> 00:11:52.960
not to others.

00:11:53.599 --> 00:11:55.559
There is local context

00:11:55.559 --> 00:11:58.799
that you can imagine like in your session output,

00:11:58.799 --> 00:12:02.559
there's information used for debugging purposes for yourself,

00:12:02.559 --> 00:12:04.840
but that again is your personal machine

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:07.840
or your personal kind of workbench instance

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:10.799
where you again own the data or have control over the data.

00:12:13.919 --> 00:12:16.159
I'll also talk a little bit about a roadmap item

00:12:16.159 --> 00:12:17.440
that we've been working on.

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:19.919
I talked about how you can fix things

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:22.280
in the Posture and Assistant sidebar chat

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:23.760
and ask a question,

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:27.119
but we're also injecting directly within the console

00:12:27.119 --> 00:12:30.119
fix and explain actions.

00:12:30.119 --> 00:12:31.679
So this basically says like,

00:12:31.679 --> 00:12:33.039
as soon as you see an error,

00:12:33.039 --> 00:12:35.200
there's a little shortcut you can do

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:36.960
to help resolve that error

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:38.359
or explain what's going on

00:12:38.359 --> 00:12:42.559
if you can't interpret the trace back kind of ad hoc.

00:12:42.559 --> 00:12:43.760
So in this exact case,

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:45.640
I've clicked on fix that

00:12:45.640 --> 00:12:48.000
and it says, oh, well, here's the trace back,

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:49.080
here's a little context

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:52.200
of what we're actually trying to fix in the error.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:54.320
And then it says, okay, along with that,

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:56.000
I've built out the structure

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:57.840
of what the project you're working on.

00:12:57.840 --> 00:13:00.000
I see the file that you're working on

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.440
and here's an interpretation of the error message

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:04.239
and how to resolve it.

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:07.840
Basically, not only just solving the problem for you,

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:09.400
but helping you understand,

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:11.799
oh, in the future, if you see something like this,

00:13:11.799 --> 00:13:15.400
here's the problem state or why it was occurring.

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:17.520
And you could have just asked it to explain

00:13:17.559 --> 00:13:20.119
or do other things or just generally chat with it,

00:13:20.119 --> 00:13:21.919
but it pops up this ephemeral chat

00:13:21.919 --> 00:13:24.000
where you can work with and again,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.520
solve those problems that are runtime errors

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:29.280
or runtime outputs and explain it there.

00:13:34.159 --> 00:13:37.159
So again, I talked a little bit about these tool calls

00:13:37.159 --> 00:13:39.719
are in addition to what I would consider table stakes

00:13:39.719 --> 00:13:42.239
features that people expect from Gen AI tools

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:44.119
and clients in your IDE, right?

00:13:44.119 --> 00:13:45.919
So again, it already has all the awareness

00:13:45.919 --> 00:13:49.119
of like the active file, the selected snippet of code,

00:13:49.119 --> 00:13:50.719
your project-wide context,

00:13:50.719 --> 00:13:54.559
and all of the training data that went into that model.

00:13:54.559 --> 00:13:57.559
But we're enhancing it with the in-memory

00:13:57.559 --> 00:14:00.440
or session level context or unique aspects

00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:02.400
that Positron is bringing to the table.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:06.479
We've got that additional things coming along

00:14:06.479 --> 00:14:08.479
where there's like inline error correction, right?

00:14:08.479 --> 00:14:10.400
The fix with assistant, right?

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.400
Again, where in your source files,

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:15.479
it directly ties there into sidebar chat,

00:14:15.479 --> 00:14:19.400
inline chat, or those static analysis errors for fixing it

00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:22.359
or the console errors and fixing it at runtime.

00:14:23.919 --> 00:14:26.159
The code generation that you might typically do

00:14:26.159 --> 00:14:27.320
if you were to go to like, you know,

00:14:27.320 --> 00:14:30.000
chat GPT or cloud on the web and say,

